### LINQ in C#

LINQ (Language Integrated Query) allows you to query data from collections, databases, XML, and more using a SQL-like syntax integrated into C#.

### Two Forms of LINQ

**Query Syntax (SQL-like):**

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 };

var result = from n in numbers
             where n > 3
             orderby n descending
             select n * n;
```

**Method Syntax (Fluent):**

```csharp
var result = numbers
    .Where(n => n > 3)
    .OrderByDescending(n => n)
    .Select(n => n * n);
```

### Basic Query Operations

```csharp
var fruits = new[] { "Apple", "Banana", "Cherry", "Date", "Elderberry" };

// Filtering
var longFruits = fruits.Where(f => f.Length > 5);

// Projection
var firstLetters = fruits.Select(f => f[0]);

// Sorting
var sorted = fruits.OrderBy(f => f.Length);

// Aggregation
int count = fruits.Count();
int totalLength = fruits.Sum(f => f.Length);
double avgLength = fruits.Average(f => f.Length);
```

### LINQ on Different Data Sources

```csharp
// In-memory collections
List<int> nums = new() { 1, 2, 3 };
var query1 = nums.Where(n => n > 1);

// Arrays
int[] arr = { 1, 2, 3 };
var query2 = arr.Select(n => n * 2);

// Strings
string text = "Hello World";
var vowels = text.Where(c => "aeiou".Contains(c));

// Databases (Entity Framework)
// var users = db.Users.Where(u => u.Age > 18);
```

### Deferred Execution

LINQ queries use deferred execution - the query is not executed until you iterate over it:

```csharp
var query = numbers.Where(n => n > 3);  // Not executed yet

foreach (var n in query)  // Executed here
    Console.WriteLine(n);

// Force execution
List<int> list = query.ToList();
int[] array = query.ToArray();
int first = query.First();
```

### Standard Query Operators

| Category | Methods |
|----------|---------|
| Filtering | `Where`, `OfType` |
| Projection | `Select`, `SelectMany` |
| Sorting | `OrderBy`, `OrderByDescending`, `ThenBy` |
| Grouping | `GroupBy`, `ToLookup` |
| Join | `Join`, `GroupJoin` |
| Aggregation | `Count`, `Sum`, `Average`, `Min`, `Max` |
| Quantifiers | `All`, `Any`, `Contains` |
| Set | `Distinct`, `Union`, `Intersect`, `Except` |
| Partitioning | `Take`, `Skip`, `TakeWhile`, `SkipWhile` |
| Element | `First`, `FirstOrDefault`, `Single`, `SingleOrDefault` |
| Conversion | `ToList`, `ToArray`, `ToDictionary`, `ToHashSet` |

> **Key Point:** LINQ works with any IEnumerable<T> source. Query syntax is more readable for complex queries; method syntax is more flexible. Queries are lazily evaluated (deferred execution). Use `ToList()` or `ToArray()` to materialize results.

### LINQ with Multiple Sources

```csharp
var cartesian = from x in new[] { 1, 2 }
                from y in new[] { 3, 4 }
                select (x, y);
// Result: (1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4)
```

### Let Clause

```csharp
var query = from s in students
            let avg = s.Scores.Average()
            where avg > 80
            select new { s.Name, Average = avg };

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Linq;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var numbers = new List<int> { 5, 2, 8, 1, 9, 3, 7, 4, 6 };

        // Query syntax
        var queryResult = from n in numbers
                          where n % 2 == 0
                          orderby n
                          select n;

        Console.WriteLine("Even numbers (query): " + string.Join(", ", queryResult));

        // Method syntax
        var methodResult = numbers
            .Where(n => n > 5)
            .OrderByDescending(n => n)
            .Select(n => n * 10);

        Console.WriteLine("Greater than 5 (method): " + string.Join(", ", methodResult));
    }
}
